label chapter4:

    # [Scene: La Marisma — Raised Walkway | Morning]

    scene bg ch4_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, buoyant strings with a hopeful lilt]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Hammers, muffled conversation, distant gulls and a low surf]
    "Narration:"
    "You left the council chamber with your voice still ringing — your public backing of Elias like a stone dropped into the barrio's pooled attention. It sent ripples: a dozen messages on your phone, Teo texting"
    "the logistics list, Sofia promising pastries and extra hands, and Elias already on the loudspeaker organizing teams."
    "Narration:"
    "You feel something like lightness and gravity braided together. There is no dramatic solitude here — only the close, busy pressure of people arranging themselves around a clear task. This is how resistance becomes infrastructure."
    show asha_rivera at left:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_rivera "Alright. We're not waiting for permission. We build, we learn, we protect each other."
    show elias_hart at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "That's the spirit. We have designs from Jun, a handful of living-seawall modules salvaged from the old university project, and the community's will. We can do this today.' 'You ready to teach them how to braid the root mats?"
    "Narration:"
    "You nod and feel your shoulders roll down, the kind of steadiness that settles in when hands know their tools. The tarp holds jute, coir, mesh, and a small stack of woven root mats you and"
    "Jun tested. The smell of wet fiber and citrus from Sofia's thermos fills the air like permission."
    show mateo_teo_rivera at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_teo_rivera "I've got the rigging and the pulley. If the tide creeps up, we shift the staging platform and keep dry. Food's on me—Sofia's putting out tamales and coffee."
    hide asha_rivera
    show sofia_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    sofia_navarro "You taught me to prune mangroves when I was a kid. Today you teach our grandkids to keep them rooted. Eat first—your hands will need fuel."
    "Narration:"
    "You accept a pastry, warmth spreading through your palm. The sugar and salt of sea air and dough is such a small human comfort; it tastes like home. Around you, people trade instructions and stories—an older"
    "pair whispering about a house they pulled through the last surge, a teenager asking whether the seedlings need fresh compost."
    hide elias_hart
    hide mateo_teo_rivera
    hide sofia_navarro

    scene bg ch4_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Soft chatter, the creak of a pulley being tested]
    "Narration:"
    "You walk the line of volunteers, voice low and precise as you demonstrate the first knot, the right spacing of root units."
    show asha_rivera at left:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_rivera "Listen—coir holds moisture, but it compacts if you overpack. Leave space for tidal flushing. Each module has to breathe. If we do this right, the roots will catch silt; over months, this becomes living armor."

    "Volunteer 1" "How long before we see results?"

    asha_rivera "Months for visible accretion; the first season we want stability. You’ll see birds come back, small fish—then more. The work pays out slowly but it compounds."
    show elias_hart at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "And while nature does its math, we hold the line. We chant, we stand—every module is a statement."
    "Narration:"
    "Jun arrives with a small tablet, eyes bright beneath his round glasses. He sets down a portable rain gauge and a stack of printouts—salinity trends, sediment forecasts. His presence steadies the technical side of the work."
    show dr_jun_park at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_jun_park "Data still supports the living approach in this stretch. Sediment supply is uncertain, but our pocket interventions can accelerate accretion if we place them perpendicular to tidal flow. Asha, you had the placement map?"

    asha_rivera "Right here.' (You tap the map pinned to a plywood easel.) 'We start at the old jetty's lee side—natural eddy, slower water. The modules will trap silt and protect the walkway."

    dr_jun_park "I'll monitor, run fortnightly salinity checks. If we see unexpected hypoxia, we pivot."
    "Narration:"
    "Your chest warms with a stubborn, honest pride. Together, the blueprint of hands and the blueprint on Jun's tablet make a single plan. People nod; you take quick, practical questions and answer them until the knotting becomes a chorus, not a lecture."

    menu:
        "Demonstrate the first root mat yourself":
            "You step into the muddy shallows and let the crowd watch your hands—wet and sure. Their faces tighten with concentration, and a young volunteer mirrors your knot with a clumsy but determined smile."
        "Let Elias lead the first install with a rousing call":
            "Elias climbs onto the staging crate and calls the team forward—his voice becomes a tide of confidence. You stand back and watch the group move as one, energized by his rhythm."

    # --- merge ---
    "'You try both in quick succession—the intimacy of a hands‑on demo and the surge of Elias's leadership. The hybrid of teaching and rallying is a good fit for today.'"
    hide asha_rivera
    hide elias_hart
    hide dr_jun_park

    scene bg ch4_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Lively banter, the slap of water on pilings, a child's delighted shriek as a crab scuttles past]
    show sofia_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    sofia_navarro "We should name this stretch. Names stick in people's mouths. They belong to places after that."
    show asha_rivera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_rivera "How about 'Cosecha Point'—for what we hope to harvest from the tide."

    sofia_navarro "Perfect. Cosecha Point it is."
    "Narration:"
    "You catch snippets of other conversations: an elder teaching the younger how to tell when a root is ready to tolerate salt, a pair of teenagers swapping protest songs between trowel strikes. Each exchange is a stitch. Each seedling is a promise you plan to keep."
    show mateo_teo_rivera at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_teo_rivera "We're short on coir and burlap. Leon's promised a donation to the mayoral fund if they approve the pilot— that's not for us. We need to scout salvage and reroute the budget—every ten meters costs."
    "Narration:"
    "Resource anxiety prickles at the base of your throat. The donor landscape is a maze: corporate offers that come with conditions, municipal grants that lag. But the crowd goes on knotting and planting as though scarcity were a rumor, not a fact. Momentum is contagious."

    asha_rivera "We'll repurpose. Old fishing nets, burlap from the market, pallets from the sanitation yard. Reuse is our currency for now."
    hide sofia_navarro
    show dr_jun_park at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_jun_park "And I'll run a materials efficiency test—see where we can shave grams without losing structure. Small changes can free up enough to keep us moving."
    hide asha_rivera
    show elias_hart at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "You're doing that thing where you make everyone believe in the plan as if you already know it will work."
    hide mateo_teo_rivera
    show asha_rivera at center:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_rivera "Someone has to believe it first."

    elias_hart "And someone has to make sure belief is matched by action. Which you do, every day."
    "Narration:"
    "There is a moment in that exchange where historical cracks close into a comfortable bridge: your collaboration with Elias has weight now, public and practical. His eyes find yours and linger, sea-glass green bright with shared"
    "resolve. The past falling-out is an undertow, but today it is diverted by the volume of community effort."

    menu:
        "Pull Elias aside and review material lists privately":
            "You whisper numbers to him at the edge of the staging platform; his face tightens with strategy. The private alignment steadies you both, and you return to the work with the same stride."
        "Keep things public—address the crowd about resource honesty":
            "You climb the crate and speak to everyone. The truth lands and is met with practical applause—people volunteer salvage routes and pledge shifts. The candidness makes the commitment feel shared."

    # --- merge ---
    "'You choose candor. You climb, voice steady, and tell the crowd where you stand—what you can commit and what you cannot. The reaction is not hand-wringing; it's a flood of solutions: a neighbor who can borrow"
    "a baler, a small team offering boat time to fetch reclaimed material, a baker promising extra tips for fund collection. Momentum builds not from certainty but from collective improvisation.'"
    hide dr_jun_park
    hide elias_hart
    hide asha_rivera

    scene bg ch4_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The strings swell into an affirming chord]
    show dr_jun_park at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_jun_park "I've routed the first monitoring schedule to the municipal node. If the mayor's office wants data, we'll give it. Transparency is our ally."
    show asha_rivera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_rivera "Good. We keep the science open and the community running the work. That's our leverage."
    show elias_hart at center:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "And I keep the streets loud. Your diligence keeps us honest."
    "Narration:"
    "Hands, work, and a few hard conversations are turning into something sturdier than argument—a public practice of resilience. You feel the barrio move under your feet like a body finding its balance. Even the children have"
    "roles: one carries a small watering can with exaggerated care, another plants a seed and stamps the soil with the solemnity of a rite."
    hide dr_jun_park
    show sofia_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    sofia_navarro "My sister lost her roof last year. That house is still there because people showed up. Today, it feels like we're paying that back."
    "Narration:"
    "You imagine future evenings here, strung lanterns and conversations about the city that once was and the city being made. The thought brightens you."
    hide asha_rivera
    hide elias_hart
    hide sofia_navarro

    scene bg ch4_453e40_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The hush of the wind shifting, a bell from the market tower]
    "Narration:"
    "As the crowd disperses into smaller crews, you take a slow walk along the boardwalk toward the Old Estuary — an impulse to watch the tide, to listen. The wooden planks sigh beneath you; the mangrove fringe rustles like an old friend."
    "Narration:"
    "You think ahead to the mayoral hearing follow-ups and Leon's possible counteroffers. There will be conversations with Aegis Tower, with policymakers who measure people as data points. For now, though, the sound of work being done"
    "is enough. Your heart beats with a rising certainty: communal labor breathes life into policy arguments. It makes them visible and urgent in a way petitions sometimes can't."

    scene bg ch4_453e40_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single violin line holds an airy, rising note]
    "Narration:"
    "You know the next steps will be tactical and political, which is to say they will be hard. But the Barrio has shown up. The modules are in the water. Children will tell tales of the"
    "first knots. People who came doubtful now measure the swelling confidence in each other's eyes."
    "Narration:"
    "You run your thumb along the edge of the map in your pocket—the ink fading where your fingers have smoothed it—and realize, with a small, sharp joy, that this is what hope looks like when it's"
    "mutual: not a solitary flame but a braided rope, thicker where hands clasp it. The wind picks up, carrying plastered posters and the scent of baking bread. Ahead, the estuary reflects a sky that seems to"
    "have decided, for the moment, to be generous."

    scene bg ch4_453e40_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Rising, optimistic motif]

    scene bg ch4_453e40_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade Out]

    jump chapter5
